1 campus of West Monroe High School in 1992, where he served as one of the top defensive
2 coordinators in the state, distinguishing himself in that position with eight state
3 championship teams; and
4 WHEREAS, he was named head coach of the Rebels in 2013, and led his team to
5 nine district championships and two state championship game appearances, compiling an
6 incredible 104-22-1 record; and
7 WHEREAS, Coach Arledge's exemplary coaching produced outstanding players and
8 helped to cultivate new careers for those players in the ranks of college and professional
9 football; and
10 WHEREAS, he proved himself to be a leader of the highest caliber, a catalyst who
11 motivated young athletes to work together, to exceed personal expectations, to attempt
12 seemingly unattainable goals, to demonstrate an exceptional competitive nature and esprit
13 de corps, and to perform as a team made of many cohesive parts; and
14 WHEREAS, Coach Arledge was honored by the National Football Foundation and
15 College Hall of Fame in 2021 for his contributions to amateur football, having worked with
16 unflagging vitality out of pure love for the game and a desire to help students play it well;
17 and
18 WHEREAS, devoted to his faith and a steadfast member of First Methodist Church
19 in West Monroe; Jerry was preceded in death by his grandson, Ben; his parents, Ruel and
20 Myrtle Arledge; and siblings, Edward Arledge, Buster Arledge, and Peggy Densmore; and
21 WHEREAS, those left to honor and cherish him are his loving wife of over sixty
22 years, the former Sally Lytton of Gilliam, Louisiana; his four children, Sara Blackwell, Will
23 Arledge (Joan), Libby Gleason (Steve), and Rob Arledge (Amanda); his grandchildren,
24 Abby, Will (Laura), Sally, Emily (Matt), Mary, Andrew, Lytton, and Sara Catherine; his five
25 great grandchildren; and a host of nieces, nephews, loved ones, and friends; and
26 WHEREAS, Jerry shall remain an enduring figure in West Monroe sports, his
27 community, and his state for many years to come; and
28 WHEREAS, he represented all that is good about Louisiana as a man with unique
29 gifts and a charitable spirit, and with his passing Louisiana has lost one of its finest citizens,
30 who left an indelible mark on the lives of the many individuals whom he touched with his
